Narcotics 

<DATE1>  4 April 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Counternarcotics Operations for 21-28 March </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Counternarcotics Operations for 21-28 March </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3103005894 </F>
<F P=103> LD3103005894 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
fileworthy reports on antidrug operations in countries monitored 
by FBIS London Bureau from 21-28 March. Sources are given in 
parentheses at the end of each report. 
<H5>  Czech Republic </H5>
  Staff of the drug administration from the criminal police 
headquarters seized 24 kilograms of heroin worth over 20 million 
crowns. They also detained two citizens of the Czech Republic 
who were transporting the drug abroad. The consignment arrived 
from Turkey and was destined for Scandinavia. The police 
followed the van carrying the drugs to the border crossing at 
Varnsdorf in North Bohemia, where they dismantled the van and 
seized the drugs. (Prague CT 1 Television Network in Czech 1830 
GMT 25 Mar 94) 
<H5>  Hungary </H5>
  Customs officers found a record amount of drugs at the 
border 
crossing point at Gyula on the Hungarian-Romanian border. They 
found nearly 150 kg of heroin in a Dutch truck coming from the 
direction of Romania. The driver was reported by the County 
Bekes police and the drugs were seized. (Budapest Kossuth Radio 
Network in Hungarian 1300 GMT 30 Mar 94) 
<H5>  Iran </H5>
  Central provincial law enforcement personnel have reportedly 
busted 10 gangs of drug dealers and seized about 222 kilos of 
narcotics, mainly opium, during the past six months. 
  Brigadier General Reza Aliyari, commander of the law 
enforcement forces, said that 316 drug dealers and 1,450 addicts 
were arrested in this connection. The forces also seized 83 
firearms and 2,000 cartridges from the traffickers. (Tehran 
IRNA in English 1434 GMT 26 Mar 94) 
  After a shootout with drug smugglers in Mohammadabad region, 
southwest of Khorasan, law enforcement forces seized 81 kg of 
opium along with 10 rifles and a pistol from the drug smugglers. 
  Khorasan shares borders with Pakistan and Afghanistan, where 
the remote rugged areas are the main centers of opium 
cultivation. (Tehran IRNA in English 1352 GMT 28 Mar 94) 
<H5>  Italy </H5>
  Police in Trieste seized 300 kilos of pure heroin, worth 
more 
than 500 billion lire. The heroin, hidden in a truck parked 
outside the port, reportedly arrived from Turkey and was bound 
for a Central European country. 
  Two foreigners were arrested, one in Trieste and one in 
Austria. Their names were not revealed. They are thought to be 
members of a criminal organization that smuggles drugs from 
Turkey to Europe. (Rome RAI Televideo Teletext in Italian 1039 
GMT 21 Mar 94) 
<H5>  Portugal </H5>
  Police have seized four tonnes of hashish in the region of 
Leiria in central Portugal. The consignment originated from 
Morocco, arrived in Portugal through the Algarve, and from there 
was to go by truck to Holland. Three men have been arrested, 
all of them Portuguese. According to police, this traffickers' 
ring is composed exclusively of Portuguese nationals, thus 
bypassing the usual Galician drugs circuit. The police expect 
to make another three arrests. (Lisbon RTP Internacional 
Television in Portuguese 1200 GMT 25 Mar 94) 
<H5>  Spain </H5>
  In Madrid police have arrested four Colombians and a 
Bolivian 
woman after seizing from them 3.3 kilos of cocaine. The drugs 
were hidden inside five tins of pineapple in syrup with the 
label of a Madrid chain of supermarkets. (Madrid RNE-1 Radio 
Network in Spanish 2200 GMT 26 Mar 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

