<H3> <TI>   Official Attributes Increase in Coca Cultivation to Peruvian </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Attributes Increase in Coca Cultivation to Peruvian </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Antidrug   Efforts 

<F P=102> PA0304130894 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0304130894 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Diego Hernan Canal; from the "NTC News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Colombian drug authorities are very concerned 
because, apparently, Peru's successful struggle against the 
people who traffic in drugs in that country has resulted in a 
significant increase in coca growing in Colombia. Authorities 
have confirmed that Bolivian and Peruvian coca crops are being 
moved to Colombia and that the number of coca plantations has 
increased 100 percent in the past four years. This prompts a 
new and distressing situation in our country. 
  [Begin Colombian Drug Director Gabriel De Vega recording] We 
are becoming a country that produces coca and are very close to 
supplanting Bolivia for second place, after Peru, as a coca 
producing country. [end recording] 
  The situation is developing as a result of Peru's struggle 
against the aircraft that transport coca base from that country 
to Colombia to be processed into cocaine. The large number of 
planes downed by the Peruvians has caused pilots involved in 
drug trafficking to decide to leave the business or to charge 
too much. 
  [Begin De Vega recording] Confronted with this situation, 
for 
example, they prefer to shift coca growing to Colombia, even if 
it is not as productive as in Peru. They would rather increase 
the number of crops to compensate for the loss in productivity. 
[end recording] 
  This situation is making Colombia not only a cocaine 
processing and marketing country, but also a coca grower as big 
as Bolivia. 

</TEXT>

