<H3> <TI>   Lawmakers Want To Question General on Alleged Military Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lawmakers Want To Question General on Alleged Military Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
to   Drug Traffickers 

<F P=102> PY2503234294 Lima EL COMERCIO in Spanish 16 Mar 94 p A4 </F>
<F P=103> PY2503234294 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima EL COMERCIO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Unconfirmed" column] </F>
  [Text] Congressman Manuel Moreyra Loredo (Sode) 
[Solidarity and Democracy] has asked Andres Reggiardo Sayan 
(NM-C90) (New Majority-Change 90), the CCD (Democratic 
Constituent Congress) Defense and Domestic Order Committee 
chairman, to summon EP (Peruvian Army) General Nicolas Hermoza 
Rios, the Armed Forces Joint Command chairman. 
  The goal of summoning Hermoza is to have him explain the 
charges filed by EP Major Evaristo Castillo Aste (Ret) and EP 
Captain Ricardo Falconi Alvarez (Ret) on alleged support 
supplied by bad military elements to notorious drug traffickers 
and their ties. 
  Moreyra's petition makes us recall what happened a few 
months 
ago when, summoned by the CCD Human Rights Committee chaired at 
that time by Roger Caceres (FNTC) (Workers and Peasants National 
Front), Hermoza Rios flatly denied that any Army members had 
anything to do with the disappearance of nine students and a 
professor from La Cantuta University and claimed that those who 
disputed his denial were conducting a campaign against our 
country's guardian institution. The following day the tanks 
were out on the streets. 
  Maybe recalling this event, Moreyra makes it clear that his 
proposal is based "solely and exclusively on the fact that the 
bad elements who are wearing uniforms our country has given them 
and are openly--and with impunity--acting against national 
interests, degrading their institution, must be thoroughly 
investigated and exemplarily punished to safeguard the image, 
credibility, and respect of our Armed Forces." 

</TEXT>

