<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> VENEZUELA </F>
<H3> <TI>   General Says Colombian `Narcoguerrillas' Increasing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    General Says Colombian `Narcoguerrillas' Increasing </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Activities   in Border Region 

<F P=102> PA0104130594 Caracas EL UNIVERSAL in Spanish 29 Mar 94 p 4-16 </F>
<F P=103> PA0104130594 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas EL UNIVERSAL </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

  [Text] Caracas, 28 Mar (VENPRES) -- Division General 
Egberto Artuza Delgado, commanding general of the National 
Guard, has indicated that there has been a gradual increase in 
the past months in activity by Colombian narco-guerrillas 
[narcoguerrilla], particularly in the Amazonian area. Artuza 
Delgado said this at the end of a meeting with Pompeyo Marquez, 
special minister for border affairs, whom he briefed on the 
prevailing situation in the border area and the operations being 
conducted there by the National Guard. 
  Artuza Delgado pointed out that the National Guard is aware 
that drug traffickers have set up cocaine processing 
laboratories and have planted cocaine fields in Colombian 
territory near the Venezuelan Amazonian area. He explained that 
the existence of these cocaine fields also draws guerrillas 
closer since they are in charge of protecting production of the 
drug. Artuza Delgado termed this situation "very serious." 
  Later, referring to the resources the National Guard needs 
for border operations, he added that the National Guard is aware 
of the country's fiscal situation and that is why it has changed 
its conduct. According to Artuza, the National Guard will have 
to learn to manage the resources assigned for border operations 
more efficiently. 

</TEXT>

