<F P=100> EAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> MALAYSIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kuala Lumpur Described as `Gathering Place' for Country's </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kuala Lumpur Described as `Gathering Place' for Country's </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Drug   Users 

<F P=102> 94WD0285A Kuala Lumpur BERITA HARIAN in Malay 23 Feb 94 p 19 </F>
<F P=103> 94WD0285A </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERITA HARIAN </F>
<F P=105>  Malay </F>
CSO 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, 22 Feb--Supplies of drugs that are 
easily obtained around the capital any time of day or night make 
the city a gathering place for drug users from all over the 
country. 
  This situation has enabled authorities to arrest many users 
in each operation it conducts, but limited detention facilities 
present authorities with problems in holding users longer for 
rehabilitation. 
  Ramil Abdul Samad, president of the Association of Former 
Drug Users (PENGASIH), said that the influx of users is because 
the capital for more than 10 years has been the center of the 
drug trade. 
  He said the drug traffic around the capital has become the 
focus of users from Pahang, Terengganu, Kelantan, Melaka, Negeri 
Sembilan, and Johor, whereas users from the north gather in 
Pulau Pinang to get supplies. 
  "Users from those areas gather in the capital because of the 
ease in obtaining supplies, and they become vagrants living in 
dark lanes and under bridges," he said. 
  He explained that limited detention space forced the 
Enforcement Directorate of the Kuala Lumpur City Council (DBKL) 
to release 40 of the 56 vagrants detained at the beginning of 
this week. 
  In a joint operation by police and the Public Welfare 
Department (JKM), vagrants were arrested in the act of injecting 
drugs into their own bodies or in a state of hallucination after 
taking drugs. Some of them were among those released. 
  Ramli said that districts around the capital where 
small-scale drug traffickers gather to provide supplies to users 
include Puduraya, Bukit Bintang, Petaling Street, and the Chow 
Kit area. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-20994 </DOCNO>
