<DATE1>  30 March 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> RUSSIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rate of Drug-Related Crimes `Rapidly' Increasing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rate of Drug-Related Crimes `Rapidly' Increasing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3003154494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1521 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3003154494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Larisa Kiskinskaya] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 30 TASS -- The number of detectives 
dealing with drug-related crimes has been recently dwindling in 
the process of reorganisation of district interior departments, 
while the rate of these crimes is rapidly increasing, according 
to Vladimir Khayretdinov, head of department for fighting 
illegal drug-trafficking. 
  Addressing a news conference on Wednesday, he reported that 
a 
total of 141 drug cases were being investigated at the moment, 
as compared with 993 drug-related crimes registered in 1992 and 
2,183 crimes registered last year. 
  The interior officer listed Ukraine and Asian regions as the 
main transshipment points on the way of drugs to Moscow. 
Non-traditional types of narcotics are smuggled from Latin 
America, while Germany supplies crack and heroin. One gram of 
quality hashish trades for 100,000 roubles on the black market, 
the same as one glass of dried poppy, one gram of heroin costs 
150 U.S. dollars. High prices force drug-addicts to commit 
grave crimes in order to pay for dope. 
  Khayretdinov stressed the need for setting up a centre to 
fight drug-trafficking, with the participation of experts in 
different fields. The first step in this direction has already 
been taken: an orphanage for children addicted to drugs is now 
functioning in Moscow's Cheremushki district. Another orphanage 
is to be opened in the south-eastern municipal district. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

