<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> KYRGYZSTAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Allocates Funds for Country's Antidrug Efforts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Allocates Funds for Country's Antidrug Efforts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3103232894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0844 
GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3103232894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Maynayev] </F>
  [Text] Bishkek, 31 March -- Kyrgyzstan has become the first 
Central Asian country allocated funds from the UN International 
Narcotics Control program. 
  Lieutenant Colonel Aleksandr Zelichenko, chairman of the 
State Commission for Narcotics Control, said today that $450,000 
were allocated for the 1994-95 period. They will be used for 
providing equipment for sub-units engaged in fighting drug 
trafficking and for training specialists. 
  Zelichenko claimed that international organizations are not 
only giving a fitting assessment of the Kyrgyz anti-drug 
services, but have also outlined a number of measures that will 
permit the republic to become integrated in the worldwide 
struggle against drug dealers. 
  Today this is necessary: via Gornyy Badakhshan and 
Kyrgyzstan 
drugs from Afghanistan have started spreading across the CIS 
republics. Via Russia, Afghan opium and marijuana wind up in 
Western Europe. This year Kyrgyzstan will be able to reach the 
Kara-Korum highway via China, which will enable Kyrgyz freight 
to get to the coast of the Indian Ocean, into India, Pakistan, 
and other countries of this region. But specialists claim that, 
together with economic advantages, the republic will become the 
object of drug dealers' close attention. Using the new route, 
they will be able to transport narcotics in both 
directions--into Asia and into Europe. It is this which is 
compelling Kyrgyzstan's law enforcement bodies to attach special 
importance to stepping up the fight against drug trafficking. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

