<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TDD-94-015-L </AU>
JPRS 
Narcotics 

<DATE1>  11 March 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army's `Campaign' To Eliminate Marijuana, Poppy Crops </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army's `Campaign' To Eliminate Marijuana, Poppy Crops </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
`Intensified' 

<F P=102>   94WB0031E Mexico City EXCELSIOR in Spanish 11 Mar 94 p 42-A </F>
<F P=103> 94WB0031E </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City EXCELSIOR </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
CSO 

  [Text] Starting yesterday, the Mexican Army intensified its 
campaign against poppy and marijuana growing throughout the 
republic, because this is the period of the greatest incidence, 
given the anticipated rainy season. 
  "Regional Operation 1994" was put into effect in the areas 
with the greatest prevalence, including Sonora, Chihuahua, 
Sinaloa, Durango, Nayarit, Jalisco, Michoacan, Guerrero, and 
Oaxaca States. A total of 9,700 members of the armed institution 
are participating. 
  This contingent is equipped with 250 field vehicles, 17 
helicopters, and seven small Mexican Air Force planes, as well 
as Army regulation weapons. 
  It also has special facilities for destroying plantations, 
including defoliants, trained dogs, flame throwers and, in some 
cases, tractors. 
  Furthermore, as the National Defense Secretariat reported, 
the campaign is not limited to those states, but extends 
throughout the country, because military personnel will be 
conducting it in their zonal and regional jurisdictions. 
  One of the important features is the surveillance at 
airports 
and on the network of roads and highways. For this purpose, the 
forces are backed by the Federal Judicial Police, whose mission 
is to detect the drug traffickers' safe houses and activities in 
all parts of the republic, so as to keep the military forces 
informed of them. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-21082 </DOCNO>
