<H3> <TI>   Minister Cites `Positive Aspects' in Report </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Cites `Positive Aspects' in Report </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0404203194 La Paz Television Nacional Network in Spanish 
1700 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0404203194 </F>
<F P=104>  La Paz Television Nacional Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

  [Text] The current Bolivian administration blames the 
previous administration for the negative report issued by the 
U.S. Government on the results of drug enforcement efforts in 
Bolivia. Our reporter Mario Espinoza has some information: 
  [Begin recording] [Espinoza] The executive branch believes 
the negative U.S. Government report on drug enforcement in 
Bolivia focuses on the first part of 1993. Social 
Communications Minister Ernesto Machicado has said the report 
contains positive aspects. He added that during its 1993 
electoral campaign, Bolivia indisputably failed to fulfill its 
commitments to the U.S. Government. 
  [Machicado] I would like to underscore three aspects. First, 
the United States will continue to cooperate with Bolivia--be it 
in drug enforcement or in any other area where cooperation 
exists. Everything will remain the same, there will be no change. 
  Second, the U.S. Embassy in Bolivia states that coca 
eradication was delayed entirely due to the administration of 
former President Jaime Paz Zamora, especially during the 
electoral campaign. Prior to the 1993 elections, the former 
Patriotic Accord administration decided to stop coca eradication 
efforts in the Chapare region basically for political and 
electoral reasons. 
  The third aspect is that the U.S. report clearly 
acknowledges 
the efforts of the current administration which has led to the 
arrest of several drug bosses and the breaking up of large drug 
rings. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

