<TEXT>
Narcotics Control Strategy Report 
<DATE1>  5 April 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> COSTA RICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Minister Plays Down Report </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Security Minister Plays Down Report </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0504033094 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 0206 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0504033094 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

  [Text] San Jose, 4 Apr (ACAN-EFE) -- Costa Rican Security 
Minister Luis Fishman today played down a U.S. State Department 
report that "money laundering" and drug trafficking and 
consumption are on the rise in Costa Rica. 
  Fishman said the report admits that "there is virtually no 
corruption" in Costa Rica's police force, which is prevented 
from taking more effective action against drug trafficking by a 
lack of financial resources. "I am proud because they say there 
is no corruption," the minister told ACAN-EFE, saying that 
contrary to what Washington says, Costa Rica has dealt "harsh 
blows" to drug traffickers in recent years despite the limited 
resources. 
  Fishman said he "disagrees" with the assertion that Costa 
Rican policemen are unprofessional. He said that Puerto Limon 
on the Atlantic coast is a problem area and added that many 
resources have been allocated to fight drug trafficking and 
consumption. 
  The State Department's annual report, released today, 
highlighted the progress made by Central American governments, 
with the exception of Nicaragua and Costa Rica, in the fight 
against drug trafficking and money laundering. The report says 
that the "laundering of drug money" is particularly serious in 
Costa Rica, Honduras, and Nicaragua, but virtually nonexistent 
in El Salvador. 
  The State Department gave Guatemala the most praise for its 
cooperation with Washington in several campaigns to eradicate 
cocaine and opium and to arrest drug traffickers. According to 
the State Department, meager resources and a lack of 
professionalism among security services preclude significant 
progress in the counternarcotics struggle in Costa Rica. 
  The report says that Puerto Limon has become the main point 
of contact between the Colombian island of San Andres, the 
Nicaraguan coast on the Caribbean, and the United States. At 
the same time, however, the report said there is virtually no 
corruption. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

