Narcotics Control Strategy Report 
<DATE1>  6 April 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> CUBA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Amat Sees Report as Possible Basis for `Deeper' Relations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Amat Sees Report as Possible Basis for `Deeper' Relations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0604185494 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1700 
GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0604185494 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

  [Text] Representatives of the Cuban and Argentine 
Governments have signed, in Havana, a bilateral cooperation 
agreement for monitoring and preventing drug addiction and drug 
trafficking. The document was signed at the Cuban Foreign 
Ministry by Alberto Lestelle, Argentine programming and 
coordination secretary for the prevention of drug abuse and for 
the antinarcotics struggle, and Cuban Minister of Justice Carlos 
Amat. 
  In exclusive statements to journalist Josefa Bussi, the 
justice minister talked about the U.S. State Department document 
that acknowledged Cuba's cooperation in the struggle against 
drug traffic. 
  [Begin Amat recording] Well, we read the statements. We have 
assessed this as something positive, because it does recognize 
the effort our country has been making--and is continuing to 
make, despite the existing difficulties in turning into concrete 
action all these things that, actually, have to do with the 
political will to fight drug trafficking, thinking not only of 
our own people but also about all mankind. We think that, 
indeed, this recognition could constitute the possibility of 
continuing to enter deeper into [continuar profundizando] the 
relations that, in an unofficial way, are being established at 
certain moments with that country's authorities. And, in the 
last analysis, it is indeed everyone's duty to continue working 
in that direction. [end recording] 
  According to the specialists, Cuba's cooperation in this 
struggle extends to intercepting planes and ships in its air and 
maritime space, as well as in supplying information to the U.S. 
services in charge of confronting that problem. 

</TEXT>

