<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Esteban Huertas G.] </F>
  [Text] "The statements by Robert Gelbard, U.S. deputy 
assistant secretary of state for inter-American affairs, are 
vague and ambiguous when he says Panama is a drug 
money-laundering center," Foreign Minister Jose Raul Mulino said 
yesterday. 
  Mulino said: "Gelbard's statements are not specific and shed 
no light on the faults committed by Panamanian authorities." 
  The foreign minister said "the administration's report does 
not give names and places where the illegalities occur." 
  Mulino says "the case to which the document alluded was the 
raid on the Gil Cafe Company, but added there was no sustaining 
evidence in the fact." [sentence as published] 
  For his part, Supreme Court Magistrate Jose Manuel Faundes 
cited "the strange U.S. attitude of discrediting Panama's image 
before the concert of nations." 
  Faundes has stressed the national authorities' cooperation 
against drug trafficking, a situation that can be brought up in 
the face of any accusation on the part of the United States. 
  The magistrate has said "Panamanian international financial 
centers have controlled money laundering, something to which 
U.S. banks can attest." 
  A U.S. delegation is visiting the country and is being 
escorted by Olegario Barrelier, president of the National 
Banking Association (ABN). 
  This visit will last until 11 April, according to 
Barrelier's 
agenda. 

</TEXT>

