<H3> <TI>   Galindo Says U.S. `Attitude' Toward Country's Antidrug </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Galindo Says U.S. `Attitude' Toward Country's Antidrug </PHRASE></F></HT>
  Efforts `Irresponsible' 

<F P=102> PA0704170194 Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 7 
Apr 94 p a2 </F>

<F P=103> PA0704170194 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ruben Dario Diaz] </F>
  [Text] Samuel Lewis Galindo, presidential candidate of the 
"National Consensus Alliance," said yesterday the United States 
has assumed an irresponsible attitude in saying Panama has not 
cooperated in the antidrug-trafficking struggle. 
  Galindo said that efforts are being made in Panama to 
cooperate in the antidrug-trafficking struggle and that the 
United States has exaggerated in saying the contrary. 
  "We are all intent on ending drug trafficking and money 
laundering once and for all in our country, because it is 
difficult to say it will end, but it is incorrect to say nothing 
has been done," he said. 
  The presidential candidate said there are authorities who 
are 
trying to fight narcotrafficking, but he added there are groups 
of criminals who attempt to evade the security system, because 
Panama is a country with vast coasts along both oceans, which 
makes it even more difficult to control. 
  Galindo also mentioned the charges against the former 
government. He said Panamanians cannot live permanently in the 
past but must learn from experiences from the past and look to 
the future, because otherwise "we will be living in the past, 
and the future will be the one that will lose." 

</TEXT>

