BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "The RPC Television News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Presidential candidate Ruben Dario Carles rejected 
accusations by some U.S. sectors linking Panama to international 
money laundering. According to Carles, Panamanians cannot 
accept everything that comes from the United States. A report 
issued by the U.S. assistant [secretary] of state for 
inter-American affairs states that Panama is one of the 
countries that offers the least cooperation in controlling drug 
trafficking and money laundering. Panamanian authorities have 
staunchly rejected this position. 
  Presidential Candidate Ruben Dario Carles, who describes 
himself as a friend of the United States, also rejected the 
allegations. 
  [Begin Carles recording] I agree with the position taken by 
Foreign Affairs Minister Jose Raul Mulino. Panama is 
cooperating in the counternarcotics effort. The enormous 
quantities of drugs seized is one indication that things are 
like they used to be, when trafficking was openly protected by 
Panamanian authorities. [end recording] 
  According to Carles, there are some isolated cases, but they 
are not enough to warrant the accusations being made against 
Panama. 
  [Begin Carles recording] We can not accept everything the 
Americans ask or demand of us. There are interests here in 
Panama that must also be defended, like the banking center. Of 
course money laundering is a crime, but it originates in the 
United States, so let us both struggle against it. They signed 
the Mutual Legal Assistance Treaty, which Panama has already 
ratified but the United States has not. [end recording] 

