<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Vilma E. Figueroa B.] </F>
  [Text] Carlos Felipe Escobar, chairman of the Legislative 
Assembly Drug Control and Eradication Committee, believes the 
United States is also responsible for the existing drug problems 
in Panama, because the Mutual Legal Assistance Treaty (MLAT) was 
approved two years ago, but the U.S. Senate still has not 
ratified it. 
  Three days ago, Robert Gelbard, U.S. deputy assistant 
secretary of state for inter-American affairs, said Panama has 
become a "very important" center for the laundering of 
narcodollars. This prompted the Panamanian Government to 
prepare a protest note which will be delivered this week to the 
authorities of President Clinton's administration. 
  "MLAT is shelved, because there are senators who have been 
unwilling to approve the treaty, which would permit both 
countries (Panama and the United States) to conduct operations 
to counter the drug problem," the president of the assembly's 
drug committee said. 
  For his part, Rodrigo Arosemena, former customs director, 
has 
said the Panamanian authorities have countered drug trafficking 
but if the U.S. authorities do not want to accept this fact, 
they should offer proof indicating otherwise. 

</TEXT>

