<F P=101> VENEZUELA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior Minister, Legislators Comment on Report, Admit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Interior Minister, Legislators Comment on Report, Admit </PHRASE></F></HT>
  Corruption Rampant 

<F P=102> PA0704042794 Caracas EL GLOBO in Spanish 6 Apr 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> PA0704042794 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas EL GLOBO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Enelcys Calderon] </F>
  [Text] "Corruption is everywhere here. It is an obstacle 
to many things in addition to the counternarcotics effort. 
Anything said about corruption in Venezuela is no 
exaggeration." Interior Minister Ramon Escovar Salom made those 
statements in Congress, where he was called to answer questions 
about a U.S. State Department report that corruption in 
Venezuela hinders the fight against drug trafficking. 
  The interior minister clarified that he had not read the 
report in question and did not have any details on this specific 
case. He did say, however, that "corruption is a very leafy 
tree in Venezuela." 
<H5>  The Legislators </H5>
  For his part, Gustavo Tarre Briceno, representative of the 
Social Christian Party and chairman of the Chamber of Deputies 
finance committee, said he had read that corruption hindered 
counternarcotics efforts just as it negatively affected any 
other government action. 
  The legislator added that he had not read the State 
Department report, which has only appeared in the press, and 
thus could not comment "on a report that only mentions Venezuela 
in a few lines. I prefer that Venezuela be evaluated by 
Venezuelans." He admitted that this type of report negatively 
affects the government. 
  MIN [National Integrity Movement] legislator Gonzalo Perez 
Hernandez said that if the U.S. Government has such information 
on Venezuela "it is probably true, because it is hard to believe 
that drug traffickers do not know the importance of politicians 
in quieting investigations that could take them or their 
representatives to jail." 
  He added that drug traffickers promote corruption in the 
government security organizations to keep drug traffickers from 
being punished. "If the United States has the names of people 
and institutions at the service of drug traffickers in our 
countries, it should identify them to help us combat drug 
trafficking and the corruption it generates." 

</TEXT>

