<H4>  Panama's Endara `Examining' Draft of Protest Note to U.S. </H4>
Government 

<F P=102> PA1204202894 Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 12 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PA1204202894 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA PRENSA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Manuel Alvarez Cedeno] </F>
  [Text] Local diplomatic sources have reported that 
President Guillermo Endara is currently examining the draft of a 
protest note that his government will officially present to the 
U.S. Government in light of a U.S. report that Panama is an 
international money laundering center. 
  Jaime Ford, the Panamanian ambassador in Washington, D.C., 
met yesterday with Foreign Minister Jose Mulino to draft the 
protest document. Government sources told LA PRENSA that the 
president is carefully analyzing the draft note before signing 
it. 
  Officials from the Clinton administration recently affirmed 
that Panama has become a major drug money laundering center. 
Endara and Foreign Minister Mulino later rejected the 
accusation. 
  Jaime Ford stated that there has been no major reaction from 
the United States since the report was released. The ambassador 
explained that ``we are working very hard to draft this protest 
note. That is the reason for my visit to the Foreign Ministry.'' 
  Last week Endara said that Panama is helping in the fight 
against drug trafficking and money laundering. 
  Ford added that the Foreign Ministry and the presidency are 
drafting the protest note together and ``will deliver it as soon 
as it is ready.'' 
  The diplomat also said that the world, as it faces the 
invasion of drugs, must create an organization that can combine 
efforts, with proper respect for the sovereignty of each nation, 
to fight drug trafficking and its effects. 
  U.S. Government sources have also said that there is more 
money being laundered in Panama now than during the days of drug 
dictator Manuel Antonio Noriega. 
  The Endara administration has rejected the charges, arguing 
that this is a campaign to tarnish the country's image. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

