<H3> <TI>     Nigeria's Abacha Expresses `Surprise' at `Pronouncement' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nigeria's Abacha Expresses `Surprise' at `Pronouncement' </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Against   Country 

<F P=102> AB1404223594 Lagos NTA Television Network in English 2000 
GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB1404223594 </F>
<F P=104>  Lagos NTA Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] The Federal Government has rejected the recent 
categorization of Nigeria by the United States of America as one 
of the four countries not cooperating with it in the fight 
against drug trafficking. The head of state, General Sani 
Abacha, stated Nigeria's objection to the classification today 
in Abuja during his maiden press briefing of media executives. 
State House correspondent Chris Nguw reports that Gen. Abacha 
described the briefing as an opportunity for forging a 
productive government-media partnership: 
  [Begin recording] Nguw: The head of 
state's briefing centered on six issues: Government-press 
relationship, the economic policy, foreign policy, the imminent 
constitutional conference, drug trafficking, and the 
Nigerian-Cameroon dispute over the Bakassi Peninsula. One of 
the highlights of the briefing was his reference to the United 
States' recent listing of Nigeria as an uncooperative country in 
the fight against drug trafficking as a political smoke screen, 
without doubt a genuine component of the United States policy on 
drug control. Gen. Abacha said the United States' pronouncement 
was a surprise, especially as Nigeria's efforts at combating 
drug trafficking are well known and have been recently applauded 
by the American Embassy in Nigeria and the United States drug 
administration. He said his administration would, however, not 
be deterred in the fight against drug trafficking. 
  Abacha: Be that as it may, it should be understood 
by all concerned that this administration is going to continue 
its fight against drug trafficking and the related crimes just 
from our concern to ensure that the drug taking culture does not 
take firm roots in our society. We shall intensify our antidrug 
crusade. Of course, we believe it is right to do so in our 
national interest and to protect our society from its cancerous 
effects that we have observed in Western societies. We urge the 
Western governments to look inwards into their own societies and 
curb the excessive appetite of their own citizens, which creates 
the demand for drugs. [applause] Nigeria does not produce any 
hard drugs. Nigerians are not a drug consuming people. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

