<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Narcotics Roundup for 11 April </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Narcotics Roundup for 11 April </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1104160394 </F>
<F P=103> PA1104160394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on regional narcotics developments monitored through 11 
April. 
  Colombia 
  Military authorities arrested five members of a gang in 
Medellin that used children between seven and 14 years of age to 
sell drugs in Antioquia neighborhood. The operation resulted in 
the seizure of 45 pounds of marijuana, 500 grams of seeds, toy 
grenades, 1 gun, 24 knives, ammunition for guns and rifles, a 
motorcycle, and notebooks given to the minors to hide the drugs. 
(Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 1 in Spanish 
1300 GMT 2 Apr 94) 
  Colombian narcotics units today seized one ton of precursor 
chemicals and captured alleged drug traffickers in Caqueta 
Department. The chemicals were hidden among 20 mattresses, 14 
boxes of napkins, and 20 bundles of toilet paper. (Mexico City 
NOTIMEX in Spanish 0016 GMT 5 Apr 94) 
  Alleged drug trafficker Samuel Alarcon Mengual, wanted by 
Colombian and U.S. authorities for drug trafficking, was 
captured today in Riohacha, northern Colombia, police sources 
reported. A television newscast, however, said Alarcon Mengual 
surrendered. (Madrid EFE in Spanish 0030 GMT 6 Apr 94) 
  Authorities reported that two drug traffickers were killed, 
four captured, and an unknown number escaped after a shoot out 
with police in a house in southern Santa Fe de Bogota, where 12 
kg of cocaine was found. (Madrid EFE in Spanish 0112 GMT 6 Apr 
94) 
  A plane transporting approximately 200 kg of cocaine to be 
dropped on the Costa Rican Pacific coast crashed near Nuqui, 750 
km northeast of Bogota. Two injured crew members were arrested, 
Colombian police reported today. The plane had a Colombian 
registration number and had departed from Villavicencio with a 
false flight plan. (Paris AFP in Spanish 2258 GMT 8 Apr 94) 
  Swiss citizen Kurt Oswald, wanted by Interpol for drug 
trafficking, was captured by police in Barranquilla as he 
attempted to leave for Aruba on a commercial flight. Oswald is 
accused of transporting drugs to Switzerland, the Netherlands, 
and France. There are several warrants for his arrest in Europe 
and Central America. (Paris AFP in Spanish 1903 GMT 9 Apr 94) 
  Police seized two gallons of concentrated liquid marijuana 
in 
Santa Fe de Bogota. Although the amount seems small, nine tons 
of marijuana leaves are needed to produce two gallons of the 
liquid, and it is four times stronger than heroin. (Santa Fe de 
Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 1 in Spanish 1800 GMT 9 Apr 
94) 
  Costa Rica 
  National Drug Control authorities dismantled one of the 
largest drug trafficking rings in southern Costa Rica during an 
operation last weekend in Neily and Pasos Canoa. Nine persons 
were arrested. (San Jose LA REPUBLICA in Spanish 29 Mar 94 p 5) 
  Guatemala 
  Treasury Guards arrested U.S. citizen Anthony Martorana 
today 
at Aurora International Airport for attempting to bring 2 kg of 
cocaine into the country. So far in 1994, authorities have 
arrested six U.S. citizens with a total of 499 kg of cocaine. 
(Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2256 GMT 6 Apr 94) 
  Honduras 
  Two alleged Guatemalan drug traffickers kidnapped two 
members 
of the Matute Donaire family in San Pedro Sula on Wednesday. 
They kidnappers were apprehended following a shoot-out with 
authorities. (Tegucigalpa LA TRIBUNA in Spanish 4 Apr 94 p 10) 
  Two alleged drug traffickers from Guatemala were arrested in 
San Pedro Sula for their involvement in a plan to bring 78 kg of 
cocaine from Nicaragua into the country in San Pedro Sula. (San 
Pedro Sula TIEMPO in Spanish 5 Apr 94 p 10) 
  Honduran counternarcotics police seized 78 kg of cocaine on 
the border with Nicaragua from two Honduran citizens following 
the arrest of two alleged Guatemalan drug traffickers in San 
Pedro Sula. The authorities reported that the cocaine, hidden in 
the false bottom of the vehicle in which the drug traffickers 
were traveling, had been picked up in Panama, taken through 
Nicaraguan, and was bound for the United States. (Panama City 
ACAN in Spanish 1725 GMT 6 Apr 94) 
  Mexico 
  Judicial Federal Police agents seized in Durango 48 kg of 
ephedrine being taken to the Unites States, confiscated 994 
grams of heroin, and arrested nine alleged drug traffickers in 
various operations in Durango, Sonora, Baja California, and 
Coahuuila. (Mexico City LA JORNADA in Spanish 4 Apr 94 p 19) 
  Judicial Federal Police seized in the past hours in various 
operations 2.6 tons of fresh marijuana valued at over $15 
million. The also seized 100 kg of ephedrine--used to enhance 
the effects of cocaine--and captured three alleged drug 
traffickers. (Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0314 GMT 5 Apr 94) 
  Soldiers destroyed approximately 20,000 poppy and marijuana 
plantations and burned more than 4.5 tons of drugs in nine 
states during the 25-day ``Region 1-94 Operation,'' it was 
reported today. Of the total amount of drugs destroyed, 46 
percent came from Chihuahua, Durango, and Sinaloa. (Mexico City 
NOTIMEX in Spanish 2127 GMT 5 Apr 94) 
  Panama 
  Customs narcotics agents seized yesterday 36 kg of cocaine 
at 
Tocumen International airport. The drug was hidden in 
industrial machine parts shipped from Santa Fe de Bogota. There 
were no arrests. (Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 6 Apr 94 p 
5a) 
  Panamanian police dismantled a drug trafficking ring made up 
of four Panamanians and two Central Americans who were 
attempting to take 66 kg of cocaine to Honduras, it was 
officially reported. The gang obtained the drug in Colombia and 
shipped it in trailers to Honduras for distribution throughout 
Central America. (Panama City ACAN in Spanish 0214 GMT 6 Apr 94) 
  Police arrested a Jamaican who had swallowed drugs valued at 
$1 million when he fainted just before boarding a plane for 
Kingston at Tocumen International Airport. (Panama City EL 
SIGLO in Spanish 8 Apr 94 p 66) 
  Venezuela 
  Judicial Technical Police arrested Venezuelan Pablo Cesar 
Ortiz Silva at Maiquetia international airport while he was 
boarding a flight for Vienna. Ortiz had swallowed 66 cocaine 
capsules. (Caracas EL NACIONAL in Spanish 2 Apr 94 p D-5) 

</TEXT>

