<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> PARAGUAY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Says Nation Lacks Resources To Fight Drugs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Says Nation Lacks Resources To Fight Drugs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1304213194 Asuncion ABC COLOR in Spanish 13 Apr 94 p 10 </F>
<F P=103> PY1304213194 </F>
<F P=104>  Asuncion ABC COLOR </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Foreign Minister Luis Maria Ramirez Boettner 
stated on 12 April that our country does not have the resources 
to combat drug trafficking or other illegal activities. He 
indicated that this is why cooperation and help from the 
consumer countries is needed, and he proposed as a solution that 
``drug trafficking has to be fought where drugs are consumed.'' 
  Former Bolivian President Jaime Paz Zamora said these same 
words when he received the U.S. demand that his country must 
fight the cultivation of coca leaf, which is the raw material 
from which cocaine is produced. 
  During the past few days our country has been involved in 
the 
trafficking of drugs or other illegal activities such as the 
Brazilian ``numbers game.'' When the foreign minister was asked 
what the government is doing to clear up the bad image that has 
been created, he said: ``I believe the government is doing 
everything it can to control drug trafficking and other illegal 
activities. We do not have sufficient resources to combat drug 
trafficking, and the help Paraguay receives from the consumer 
countries is not very much.'' 
  He indicated that the government cannot perform miracles 
without the necessary resources. He stated that our country has 
requested cooperation and help from the consumer countries, 
``because drug trafficking must be fought where the drugs are 
consumed. Because if there is consumption and an important 
price, then without a doubt there will be production and the 
possibility of [drug] routes.'' 
  He then proposed another solution to this scourge: that the 
consumer countries emphasize aiding the countries where the drug 
is produced or countries where drug routes are discovered. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

