<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> PERU </F>
<H3> <TI>   Retired Army Major Charges Bellido, Other Officers Protected </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Retired Army Major Charges Bellido, Other Officers Protected </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Traffickers 

<F P=102>   PY1204214694 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2325 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1204214694 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

  [Text] Lima, 11 Apr (EFE) -- It was disclosed today that a 
high-ranking Peruvian Army chief has been accused of heading a 
military organization that protected drug traffickers in 
exchange for money. 
  General Eduardo Bellido, current Peruvian military attache 
in 
Israel, was charged by retired Major Evaristo Castillo with 
letting drug traffickers operate in Huallaga, where he was 
political-military commander during 1991 and 1992. 
  Castillo, who said he has been harassed and received death 
threats, asserted that in 1992 Bellido ordered his troops not to 
intervene in the struggle against drug trafficking and that they 
only fought terrorism. 
  The retired Army major stated that the alleged links 
Peruvian 
military officers maintained with the drug mafias ``are a 
complete system'' and that it is not only isolated cases of 
corruption involving certain officers. 
  He thus disagreed with a recent U.S. State Department report 
stating that one of the obstacles facing the fight against drug 
trafficking in Peru is the corruption of police and military 
officers, but that the problem does not have an institutional 
character. 
  Castillo stated that in 1992 he witnessed how chiefs of 
battalions under Bellido's command collected protection fees 
from drug traffickers to let them operate and then handed that 
money over to Bellido. 
  As an example he mentioned that the general never ordered 
the 
arrest of the most important Peruvian drug trafficker, Demetrio 
Chavez Penaherrera, aka Vaticano, arrested last February in 
Colombia, ``although he knew where he was through Intelligence 
Service and DEA reports.'' 
  He also asserted that the Peruvian military also knows where 
Colombian trafficker Waldo Vargas, aka Ministro, operates and is 
not doing anything to arrest him. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-21212 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptdd017__l94055" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TDD-94-017-L </AU>
JPRS 
Narcotics 

<DATE1>  5 April 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> PERU </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Respect' for Human Rights Now a `Conscientious Action' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Respect' for Human Rights Now a `Conscientious Action' </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
During   Drug Arrests 

<F P=102> PY1204222694 Lima EL PERUANO in Spanish 5 Apr 94 p A7 </F>
<F P=103> PY1204222694 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima EL PERUANO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

  [Text] Respect for the human rights of those arrested on 
drug trafficking charges in the Upper Huallaga zone is no longer 
a cold guideline given by the military and police commands. It 
is now a conscientious action taken by all members of the Army 
and the National Police operating in that part of the Peruvian 
jungle. 
  On 2 April in San Martin, an inhospitable area in the 
Tarapoto jungle, a Dinandro [National Antidrug Division] patrol 
supported by the Air Police detected a lab for processing 
cocaine base and acted by surprise. Not even the torrential rain 
or the thunderstorm stopped police, who arrested five people. 
  After the operation, police seized 128 kg of cocaine base, 
many ingredients for making the drug, and a shotgun. 
  Back at the Tarapoto airport the arrested were taken to the 
police station. The police then, without knowing reporters were 
present, gave the arrested soft drinks and their own food 
rations they used in their operations. 
  None of the arrested showed signs of violence on their 
bodies 
when they were put under the jurisdiction of judicial officials. 
They also never complained about being mistreated by police. 
  A police sergeant said: ``We always respect the rights of 
the 
people we arrest, even under the most adverse circumstances 
after they use their weapons on us and we capture them.'' 
  This National Police action, without the tempting presence 
of 
cameras and microphones, shows that human rights are indeed 
respected in Peru and that there is no need for ``spokesmen'' 
abroad to report alleged human right violations. The real 
situation is in that remote region where perhaps one of those 
``spokesmen'' never saw what happened. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-21213 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptdd017__l94056" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TDD-94-017-L </AU>
JPRS 
Narcotics 

<DATE1>  4 April 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> PERU </F>
<H3> <TI>   Puerto Maldonado Reportedly `Chosen' as New Center for </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Puerto Maldonado Reportedly `Chosen' as New Center for </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Shipping   Drugs 

<F P=102> PY1804224594 Lima EL COMERCIO in Spanish 4 Apr 94 p A13 </F>
<F P=103> PY1804224594 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima EL COMERCIO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by ``special correspondent'' Jose Antonio </F>
Indacochea Alvarez] 
  [Text] Puerto Maldonado -- Since mid-1993, Peruvian and 
foreign drug traffickers have chosen Puerto Maldonado as the 
shipping center and exit point for drugs produced in Peru in 
their attempt to dodge the cordon established by the security 
forces in the traditional cocaine production areas. 
  This was proved by three operations carried out by the armed 
and police forces during the past five weeks, during which the 
largest amounts of drugs were seized. 
  A total of 3.5 metric tons of washed cocaine base paste were 
seized on 26 February at Boca Manu airport and more than 1 
metric ton of cocaine base paste on 24 and 26 March at an 
airstrip in Inapari, capital of Tahuamani Province. 
  In every case the cocaine was ready to be loaded on an 
aircraft bound for Colombia, where it was going to be made into 
cocaine hydrochloride that would then be sold in the United 
States and Europe. 
  It was disclosed that the drugs seized in Boca Manu belonged 
to the ``Cachique Rivera firm'' and that Colombians were 
involved. 
  It also was disclosed that the drugs seized during the two 
latest operations at Inapari airstrip and the Santa Rosa de 
Fatima farm (15 km from the Shirimayoc checkpoint on the 
Brazilian border) allowed the breaking up of another ``firm'' 
that supplied drugs to an organization of Colombian drug 
traffickers headed by an individual identified as ``Guido 
Correa.'' 
  PNP [Peruvian National Police] General Sixto Gutierrez, head 
of the PNP 10th Region, told an EL COMERCIO correspondent that 
``Guido Correa'' lives in Cauca Valley (Colombia), from where he 
directs his organization. 
  In view of the harassment by security forces in Upper 
Huallaga, Ucayali, and Ayacucho (where his aircraft used to land 
to load drugs), he decided to find another place for his 
shipments. 
  For this reason he sent to Peru six members of his 
organization identified as ``Andres,'' ``Dario,'' ``Tarzan,'' 
``Bebito,'' ``Lazo,'' and ``Cucaracha,'' who clandestinely 
entered the country between 14 and 15 March through the 
``Palestina Peru'' area on the border of La Convencion (Cuzco) 
and Ayacucho. They were received there by Peruvian citizen 
``Caliche,'' with whom they made their first contacts. 
  From there they decided to send to Inapari Colombians Miguel 
Manosalva Contreras, 26, Ruben Dario Arango Santa, 35, and 
Andres Ramirez Piedraita, 32, as well as Brazilian Alsimar 
Marquez Da Silva, to buy drugs. 
  Once in Inapari they contacted ``Fernando,'' who is the 
organization's coordinator and, with ``Piston,'' the main drug 
supplier. 
  Thus they managed to gather an initial amount of 400 kg of 
cocaine base paste, which they shipped to Colombia on 20 March. 
Since they saw that there seemed to be no problems they decided 
to continue operating in Inapari and, what is more, built an 
airstrip on the Santa Rosa de Fatima farm. 
  The Army and the PNP, however, thanks to intelligence work, 
found out about this new organization and carried out an 
operation that allowed them to seize more than 1 metric ton of 
cocaine base paste and arrest 23 drug traffickers. Two 
policemen also are being investigated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

