<F P=100> WEST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> DENMARK </F>
<H3> <TI>   National, Local Drug Policies, Treatment Programs Being </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    National, Local Drug Policies, Treatment Programs Being </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Reevaluated 
<H4>    Greater Family Involvement in Treatment Envisioned </H4>

<F P=102> 94WD0269E Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE in Danish 28 Feb 94 
pp 1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> 94WD0269E </F>
<F P=104>  Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE </F>
<F P=105>  Danish </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Lotte Mejlhede and Mikkel Thrane: ``Family Will </F>
Participate in Treatment''] 
  [Text] Involvement and responsibility are the code words 
for Social Affairs Minister Yvonne Herlov Andersen as she 
describes her vision of the drug world. Specifically, she wants 
to spend 20 million kroner to copy a treatment model used in 
Italy. 
  The model is called the ``Human Project'' and it comes from 
the solidarity center in Rome. The project is based on the idea 
that both the addict and his family will participate in the 
therapy. To a great extent, it is the family's responsibility to 
see that ``its'' black sheep gets back on his feet again. The 
drug addict enters a contractual agreement. If he breaks the 
contract, he must face the consequences. 
  ``To a far greater extent than now, drug addicts in Denmark 
will be responsible for their own survival. At the same time, 
their private network will take on more of the burden. The work 
that both the addict and his family perform at the treatment 
center, such as cleaning, cooking, and repair work, will be 
necessary to make the whole system work,'' Andersen said. 
  ``Danes have gotten used to the idea that the authorities 
will pull the addict through. Consequently, the Italian model 
cannot immediately replace traditional treatment. It will take 
several generations before we no longer simply step over those 
who are lying around on Stroget. But trial projects could be a 
starting point,'' the minister said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-21235 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptdd017__l94078" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TDD-94-017-L </AU>
JPRS 
Narcotics 

<DATE1>  1 March 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> WEST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> DENMARK </F>
<H3> <TI>   National, Local Drug Policies, Treatment Programs Being </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    National, Local Drug Policies, Treatment Programs Being </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Reevaluated 
<H4>    Social Welfare Minister's Proposal Backed </H4>

<F P=102> 94WD0269H Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE in Danish 1 Mar 94 p 
11 </F>

<F P=103> 94WD0269H </F>
<F P=104>  Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE </F>
<F P=105>  Danish </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Lotte Mejlhede and Mikkel Thrane: ``Drug </F>
Families Included In Therapy''] 
  [Text] Most Danish families would gladly offer help to get 
their loved ones back on the right track after a period of drug 
abuse, many drug-treatment providers believe. 
  Yesterday, newly elected Social Welfare Minister Yvonne 
Herlov Andersen (Democratic Center) proposed that the government 
spend approximately 20 million kroner on two pilot projects 
involving drug treatment according to the Italian model, in 
which both the family and the addict have considerable 
responsibility seeing that treatment is successful. 
  The Danish drug-treatment providers would like to draw 
families into their work, but they warn against simply borrowing 
another country's treatment system. 
  ``Italian and Danish culture differ significantly. Down 
there, there is a much stronger tradition of families that go in 
and assume responsibilities that are public responsibilities 
here in Denmark,'' said Peter Ege, social welfare physician in 
Copenhagen. 
  However, he believes that, in general, it is a good idea to 
utilize the resources of the family. 
  ``We must not believe that family therapy is our only 
salvation, but my experience is that even relatively weak 
families have something to offer,'' said Anders Gormsen, head of 
the Church Army's institution for the treatment of young drug 
addicts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
